00:07:05.671 --> 00:07:09.528
to add more stations, and to continue to connect the city.

00:07:10.948 --> 00:07:15.418
By the 1870s, technological developments meant that these underground

00:07:15.428 --> 00:07:20.728
train lines could be dug and built much deeper, far below the city,

00:07:21.038 --> 00:07:25.998
but even these deeper lines still used more traditional steam trains.

00:07:26.938 --> 00:07:31.648
These thin, narrow tunnels were drilled to almost exactly the width of the

00:07:31.648 --> 00:07:36.128
trains in the shape of a tube, which is where the name ‘the tube’ comes from.

00:07:37.578 --> 00:07:44.388
And although these underground networks existed in the 1860s and 1870s, they didn’t become

00:07:44.388 --> 00:07:51.068
entirely practical or popular until they began running on electricity in the late 1880s.

00:07:52.168 --> 00:07:57.478
What's more, for the first 70 years of its existence, the London underground

00:07:57.628 --> 00:08:02.868
was still owned and operated by a series of different private companies, which

00:08:02.868 --> 00:08:07.908
meant that efforts to expand and invest in it weren’t particularly coordinated.

00:08:09.018 --> 00:08:15.948
But after it was brought into public ownership in 1933, things really started to change

00:08:16.378 --> 00:08:21.548
- decisions could be more long-term, rather than made with the aim of short-term profit.

00:08:22.468 --> 00:08:27.688
And clearly when you need to invest lots of money to dig large tunnels underground and

00:08:27.858 --> 00:08:33.708
you are creating a public, not private transport system, long term thinking is important.

00:08:34.818 --> 00:08:40.258
Now, before we move on with our historical journey, I want to alert you to another

00:08:40.288 --> 00:08:45.638
revolutionary aspect of the London Underground from 1933, the year that it was

00:08:45.648 --> 00:08:51.008
brought into public ownership, and that is the map of the London Underground.

00:08:52.408 --> 00:08:58.588
If you can imagine the map of the London underground, it's a series of more or less straight lines.

00:08:59.048 --> 00:09:02.148
It looks more like an electricity grid than a geographical

00:09:02.168 --> 00:09:07.368
map, and that’s actually by design, it's on purpose.

00:09:08.318 --> 00:09:12.928
It was created in 1933 by a man called Harry Beck.

00:09:13.788 --> 00:09:16.798
He wasn’t a map drawer, a cartographer.

00:09:17.318 --> 00:09:23.208
He was actually an electrical draughtsman, someone who draws electrical circuits.

00:09:24.158 --> 00:09:26.758
And he was something of a revolutionary.

00:09:27.388 --> 00:09:31.698
When he was asked to create a map of the Underground, he decided to

00:09:31.798 --> 00:09:37.058
base it on an electrical circuit board, not on traditional map design.

00:09:38.128 --> 00:09:41.738
His map didn’t accurately reflect the distance between

00:09:41.738 --> 00:09:45.198
stops, or whether the line snaked left or right.

00:09:45.938 --> 00:09:50.889
His map was beautifully simple; a series of more or less straight lines.

00:09:52.079 --> 00:09:56.996
In fact, it was initially rejected, because it was too radical.

00:09:58.286 --> 00:10:02.886
But after some testing on members of the public, it was introduced.

00:10:03.206 --> 00:10:06.976
It did exactly what it needed to - it showed people what

00:10:07.016 --> 00:10:11.166
direction they needed to go, north or south, east or west.

00:10:11.226 --> 00:10:15.612
It showed people how to get  from A to B, and didn’t

00:10:15.622 --> 00:10:20.322
include superfluous, confusing or unnecessary information.

00:10:21.392 --> 00:10:28.122
And, as you may know, this model is used for most underground maps around the world today, they tend

00:10:28.132 --> 00:10:34.902
to be simple, with straight lines, and opt for user simplicity rather than geographical accuracy.

00:10:36.432 --> 00:10:38.052
Now, back to our story.

00:10:38.622 --> 00:10:42.902
Now in public ownership, there were big plans to expand the underground,

00:10:43.042 --> 00:10:47.132
but these had to be put on pause when the Second World War broke out.

00:10:48.112 --> 00:10:53.332
But that didn’t mean that the London underground lay empty and unused during the war.

00:10:54.062 --> 00:10:55.462
Far from it, in fact.

00:10:56.342 --> 00:11:00.352
As you may know, during the Second World War the London underground was

00:11:00.362 --> 00:11:05.492
used as a bomb shelter, a place for Londoners to hide from the Nazi bombs.

00:11:07.062 --> 00:11:11.392
Though the early tube network had also been used for shelter during the First

00:11:11.402 --> 00:11:16.122
World War, it was nothing like the 1940s, when the intensity of the Blitz,

00:11:16.172 --> 00:11:20.692
the German bombing campaign, forced thousands of Londonders underground.

00:11:21.712 --> 00:11:27.662
London’s tube stations doubled as air raid shelters, with thousands of men, women

00:11:27.662 --> 00:11:33.072
and children sleeping on the station platforms, the walkways, and even on the tracks.

00:11:33.712 --> 00:11:37.112
There were so many people down there, in fact, that tickets

00:11:37.112 --> 00:11:41.522
were introduced to make sure stations didn’t become overcrowded.

00:11:42.632 --> 00:11:46.692
And because these German air raids went on for so long, there

00:11:46.692 --> 00:11:51.252
was even a special train service, known as the ‘Tube Refreshments

00:11:51.262 --> 00:11:55.372
Special’, that delivered food and drinks to the sheltering Londoners.

00:11:56.462 --> 00:12:01.822
And interestingly, the Underground didn’t only provide shelter for the people of London.

00:12:02.832 --> 00:12:07.762
Part of the Picadilly line was used to store artefacts and treasures from

00:12:07.762 --> 00:12:12.422
the British Museum, including the famous but controversial Elgin Marbles.

00:12:14.092 --> 00:12:18.862
When the war ended, the tube network continued expanding in order to keep up with

00:12:18.862 --> 00:12:23.832
London’s growing population, as it had done when it first opened in the 1860s.

00:12:24.462 --> 00:12:29.179
More lines were laid, more stations opened, the routes spreading further and further

00:12:29.179 --> 00:12:34.022
across the city, creating this sprawling network that extends across the city today.

00:12:35.342 --> 00:12:41.332
Interestingly, however, there is one part of London where the tube didn’t expand to.

00:12:41.712 --> 00:12:43.072
Or not much, anyway.

00:12:43.982 --> 00:12:47.672
If you have visited London, you might have realised that there’s a

00:12:47.682 --> 00:12:52.442
noticeable difference between the tube service in north and south London,

00:12:52.752 --> 00:12:56.202
between the north side of the river and the south side of the river.

00:12:57.282 --> 00:13:01.582
In fact, there are only 31 tube stations south of the

00:13:01.582 --> 00:13:06.402
river Thames, whereas there are 250 north of the river.

00:13:07.552 --> 00:13:11.232
Several underground lines, including the Circle, Central,

00:13:11.432 --> 00:13:15.702
Hammersmith & City and Metropolitan lines don’t even go to south London.

00:13:16.582 --> 00:13:18.082
So, why is that?

00:13:18.672 --> 00:13:20.732
Well, there are two main reasons.

00:13:21.402 --> 00:13:26.662
The first is to do with geology, that is, the type of soil, the ground.

00:13:27.642 --> 00:13:32.512
Put simply, the soil in south London contains a lot of sand and other

00:13:32.512 --> 00:13:35.862
deposits that make it more difficult to build underground tunnels.

00:13:37.092 --> 00:13:40.722
The soil in north and central London, however, is mostly made

00:13:40.732 --> 00:13:44.382
up of clay and is much easier to drill and tunnel through.

00:13:46.092 --> 00:13:51.272
The second reason is that when the first lines began to open in the 1860s,

00:13:51.642 --> 00:13:56.922
south London was already quite well-covered by railway, that is, by normal train

00:13:56.942 --> 00:14:01.902
stations, so there simply wasn’t much of a need to add more track underground.

00:14:03.102 --> 00:14:09.772
The result is what you see today - south London has very poor underground connections, which often

00:14:09.772 --> 00:14:15.492
leads to people in North London complaining about having to travel south, because it takes so long.

00:14:16.322 --> 00:14:21.892
Sure, there are more overground trains, and decent bus connections, but in general

00:14:22.022 --> 00:14:27.222
it takes longer to get around, and much longer to get into central London, meaning

00:14:27.362 --> 00:14:31.202
that south London is generally a cheaper area to live in than north London.

00:14:32.262 --> 00:14:34.992
Now, back to the history of the underground.

00:14:35.522 --> 00:14:40.652
From the post-war period right through to the present day it has undergone near-constant

00:14:40.662 --> 00:14:45.562
enlargements and improvements, with the most recent being the opening of the “Elizabeth

00:14:45.612 --> 00:14:50.272
Line”, named after Queen Elizabeth, which was opened a few months before her death.

00:14:51.702 --> 00:14:57.872
And in 2023, 160 years after the first passengers chugged along through

00:14:57.872 --> 00:15:02.802
that smoky tunnel, it remains a living artefact of a technological

00:15:02.812 --> 00:15:07.252
breakthrough that has been emulated in almost 200 cities worldwide.

00:15:08.122 --> 00:15:13.122
So if your city has a subway system with a slightly odd looking map,

00:15:13.432 --> 00:15:17.762
it can probably trace its roots back here, to the London Underground.

